@node intro "Introduction"
@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}
@{jleft}
	AmiStatus is an attempt at a "centralized" notification system loosley inspired
by the Linux libnotify system, another proggy on Aminet I found (@{"Infowin" system "c:openurl http://aminet.net/package/util/rexx/InfoWin10"}), and the (blech)
M$ Windoze icon tray. In reality, its pretty much a dummy panel that AREXX scripts can
dump text into. However, it uses MUI, so it can be prettied up a good deal. 
	Like Infowin, it requires a "from" name (application name if you look at one
part of the source code, notifier name in another. Was a bit indecicive there.), a
priority, and a message. The application name can be a program, a more general label
(e-mail, chat, crash, etc...), your dogs name, the 1st ingredient of your grandmothers
favorite cookie recipe, your.. uh.. never mind... I should really drink more coffee
before doing the documentation...
	Another thing you can do do is add an icon image for various applications, so
when you get an e-mail, YAM (or simplemail, pine, whatever) can use its internal event-
handling system to send an AREXX message to AmiStatus with "email" as the message name
(remembering AREXX's quirky handling of case-sensativity can prevent massive headaches,
btw...), and AmiStatus will match the application label "email" with a pretty e-mail
icon that will pop up in the window (or an ugly one if you prefer).
@{jcenter}@{b}Not yet implemented!@{ub}
@{jleft}
	AmiStatus also logs up to 100 lines of entries before clearing out the log (it
dumps it into a log file first), which is displayable with a nlist pop-up. If 100
entries is a bit much to scroll through, you can limit that, too. Anyway, I'm babbling
again. Will continue writing in the morning. I've gone cross-eyed looking for 
extra/missing semi-colons, double ], ), [, and ( characters, and figuring out exactly
how unforgiving a typo in a realloc() statement can be on an OS with no protected memory.
@endnode

@node usage "Usage instructions"
@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}Usage@{ub}@{uu}
@{jleft}
	You start it like any icon-launched program (double-clicking), or from the 
wbstartup folder (its designed for the latter). When you first start it, the preferences
window pops up (and will keep doing so until you save the preferences), allowing you to
customize how it dispslays new events and such. There's 3 tabs in the window:
@{jcenter}@{"Main preferences" link "pics/mainprefs.iff/MAIN"}
@{jleft}
	@{b}Move Panel@{ub}		Opens a @{"window" link "pics/move.iff/MAIN"} to move the @{"panel" link "pics/panel.iff/MAIN"}.
		
	@{b}Move PopUp@{ub}		Opens a @{"window" link "pics/move.iff/MAIN"} to move the @{"PopUp Window" link "pics/popup.iff/MAIN"}.
		
	@{b}Borderless@{ub}		Makes the @{"panel window" link "pics/panel.iff/MAIN"} borderless.
		
	@{b}Gauge@{ub}			Won't hide the gas gauge when not in use.
	
	@{b}Panel@{ub}			Shows the @{"panel window" link "pics/panel.iff/MAIN"}.
	
	@{b}Popups@{ub}			En/Dis-ables @{"Popup windows" link "pics/popup.iff/MAIN"}.
	
	@{b}Images@{ub}			Disables logo and app images in the @{"pop-ups" link "pics/popup.iff/MAIN"}.
	
	@{b}AmiStatus events@{ub}	En/Dis-ables AmiStatus-specific messages.
	
@{jcenter}@{u}Priority settings:@{uu}
@{jleft}
	@{b}Hide Messages under...@{ub}	Hides any @{"Pop-up" link "pics/popup.iff/MAIN"} under set priority.
	
	@{b}Mark Messages urgent...@{ub}	Any @{"Pop-up" link "pics/popup.iff/MAIN"} over this priority is "Urgent".
	
@{jcenter}@{u}Message Test:@{uu}
@{jleft}
	The items here allow you to compose and send a message without having to mess
around with an AREXX script, or the RX command.

@{jcenter}@{"Programs" link "pics/programsprefs.iff/MAIN"}
@{jleft}	
	The listview here shows all the programs you can modify. "Program" is simply
the name of the program argument in the @{"newmessage" link newmsg} AREXX command.
	
	@{b}Program@{ub}	Program name that applies to the settings.
	
	@{b}Pop-Up?@{ub}	You can disable @{"pop-ups" link "pics/popup.iff/MAIN"} for the program here.
	
	@{b}open message@{ub}	1st line of a message that will show the programs @{"panel" link "pics/panel.iff/MAIN"} icon.
	
	@{b}close message@{ub}	1st line of a message that will hide the programs @{"panel" link "pics/panel.iff/MAIN"} icon.
	
	@{b}Click action@{ub}	Command to execute if a user clicks on the programs @{"panel" link "pics/panel.iff/MAIN"} icon.
	
	@{b}Image@{ub}		Path to the programs @{"panel" link "pics/panel.iff/MAIN"} icon.
	
	The text/check gadgets below the listview should be self-explainitory :). The
one "dead" image is the result of a yet-unfixed bug, don't worry too much about it. ;)

@{jcenter}@{"Events" link "pics/eventsprefs.iff/MAIN"}
@{jleft}
	@{b}Program events list@{ub}	Lists the programs, and the events to launch.
	
		@{u}Program@{uu} is the name to trigger an event.
		
		@{u}Message@{uu} the message that will trigger the event if the program calls.
		
		@{u}Command@{uu} The CLI (or AREXX, if "rx script.rexx" is used) to launch.
		
		@{u}Args@{uu} The Cli program's arguments.
		
	@{b}Add@{ub}			Add an event to the list ("** EDIT ME **")
	
	@{b}Remode@{ub}			Remove selected event from the list.
	
	@{b}Various string gadgets@{ub}	Should be self-explainitory :).
	
@endnode

@node reqs "System requirements"
@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}System requirements@{ub}@{uu}
@{jleft}
	This is a pretty modest program, so the requirements shouldn't be too much. so
far, I've tested it on an Amiga 1200 (AGA), with a 68030 and 8mb RAM, with no problems.
I'll do more extensive testing under emulation, however, to get a better idea. I know
it requires the following 3rd party software:
@{jcenter}@{b}Required@{ub}
@{jleft}
	@{"MUI" system "c:openurl http://aminet.net/package/util/libs/mui38usr"}		MUI 38
	
	@{"BetterString" system "c:openurl http://aminet.net/package/dev/mui/MCC_BetterString-11.23"}	Betterstring_MCC

@{jcenter}@{b}Optional@{ub}
@{jleft}
	@{"BetterString68k" system "c:openurl http://aminet.net/package/dev/mui/MCC_BetterString_68k"}	Might work for non >020 systems.
	
	@{"OpenURL" system "c:openurl http://aminet.net/search?query=openurl"}		For opening HTTP links from the AmigaGuide.
	
@endnode

